{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T16-40-32-997Z","slug":"just-add-more-engineers-fallacy","locale":"hi","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T16:43:20.825Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--just-add-more-engineers-fallacy/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--just-add-more-engineers-fallacy/hi/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/just-add-more-engineers-fallacy/hi/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T16-40-32-997Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"19d4e894c77ccbd78dd0b886180ccd67f0ff567747c4195587dd7e4e0bb8e883","outputHash":"d8116fa9fe225a7976cd36e57b48fb6dd3404933a9468b63c622e835d414165f","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that increasing team size to accelerate software projects is a flawed strategy due to exponential coordination costs, framed by the mathematical formula *n(n-1)/2* for communication paths. It critiques the assumption that work scales linearly with headcount, citing research (Microsoft’s DevDiv, *Accelerate*, *The Mythical Man-Month*) to highlight how onboarding delays, mentorship overhead, and domain knowledge gaps negate productivity gains. Smaller, autonomous teams (e.g., Amazon’s \"two-pizza rule\") and modern tools like CI/CD reduce but cannot eliminate these costs, emphasizing Brooks’ Law: adding engineers to a late project delays it further. The tone is analytical and cautionary, targeting engineering managers and leaders tempted to prioritize speed over team dynamics. Key metaphors include pregnancy timelines and archaeological digs to underscore the inescapable human and contextual challenges in software development.","totalInputTokens":9587,"totalOutputTokens":13571,"totalCacheReadTokens":0,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":145173,"totalCostUsd":0.004024,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChu